out 1265–Deceased","1262–Male":"1262–Deceased","1299–Female":"1299–Deceased","1265–Female":"1265–Deceased","Abt 1265":"about 1265","Abt 1287":"about 1287","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","about 1299":"about 1299","1262":"1262","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Hankelow, Cheshire":"Hankelow, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bechton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern) and Scottish: habitational name from Beckton near Lockerbie in Dumfriesshire. The placename is from Old Norse <i>bekkr</i> ‘beck, stream’, + <i>tūn</i> ‘farm, village’. The surname is not from Beckton in East Ham (Essex), which is named for the 19th-century gas and coal magnate S. A. Beck. Compare   Becton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Becton","meanings":["Scottish and English: altered form of   Beckton  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Robert De Bechton II was born about 1265, in Hankelow, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Robert de Bechton II about 1287, in Hankelow, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1265–":"umbes 1265–Surnud","1262–Male":"1262–Surnud","1299–Female":"1299–Surnud","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","Abt 1265":"umbes 1265","Abt 1287":"umbes 1287","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","about 1299":"umbes 1299","1262":"1262","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Hankelow, Cheshire":"Hankelow, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1265–":"noin 1265–Kuollut","1262–Male":"1262–Kuollut","1299–Female":"1299–Kuollut","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","Abt 1265":"noin 1265","Abt 1287":"noin 1287","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","about 1299":"noin 1299","1262":"1262","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Hankelow, Cheshire":"Hankelow, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1265–":"environ 1265–Décédée","1262–Male":"1262–Décédé","1299–Female":"1299–Décédée","1265–Female":"1265–Décédée","Abt 1265":"environ 1265","Abt 1287":"environ 1287","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","about 1299":"environ 1299","1262":"1262","Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre","Hankelow, Cheshire":"Hankelow, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs Robert De Bechton II est née environ 1265, à Hankelow, Cheshire, Ang